## Phase 7: Web UI — User Management Admin Page

A new route `/admin/users`, accessible only to Admin-role sessions. Link it from the existing `/admin` page (Workers).

### User list

Table showing all users:

| Email | Role | Last login | Actions |
|-------|------|------------|---------|
| admin@example.com | Admin | 3 days ago | (role dropdown) |
| editor@example.com | Editor | 1 week ago | (role dropdown) (remove) |
| viewer@example.com | Viewer | never | (role dropdown) (remove) |

- **Role dropdown**: `Admin / Editor / Viewer`. On change, calls `PATCH /v1/users/{user_id}`.
  - If the server returns `409 last_admin`, show "Cannot demote the last admin".
  - A user cannot change their own role (disable the dropdown for the current user's row).
- **Remove button**: calls `DELETE /v1/users/{user_id}` after a confirmation prompt ("Remove {email}? They will lose access immediately.").
  - If the server returns `409 last_admin`, show "Cannot remove the last admin".
  - Not shown on the current user's own row.

### Create user form

Below the table or in a slide-over panel:

```
Email    ____________________
Password ____________________
Role     [Admin ▾]
         [Create user]
```

Calls `POST /v1/users`. On success, the new user appears in the table. On `409`, show "Email already registered".

### Access control

If a non-Admin navigates to `/admin/users`, the page returns a 403 from the API and the UI shows "Admin access required". The route itself is not hidden — obscuring it provides no security since the API enforces it.

